Less than 10% of EU aid money reaches the countries where it is most needed,
according to a study that found levels of assistance had dropped for the
second year running

The EU and its member states remain the biggest development donor group in the
world ? investing ?71 9bn (‚Ç¨61bn) in 2018, more than half of global aid ? but
its contribution was 5 8% lower than in 2017, the European NGO network,
Concord, found in its AidWatch report

Progress on meeting the UN target of spending 0 7% of gross national income on
aid, laid down in 1970, has gone into reverse, said the group Their research
showed that aid decreased to 0 47% of the EU?s combined GNI last year,
compared with 0 49% in 2017 and 0 51% in 2016

Advertisement

Only Sweden, Luxembourg, Denmark and the UK met the 0 7% commitment

The UK?s three main political parties have committed to retaining the aid
target

Aid from five countries ? Italy, Greece, Finland, Austria and Lithuania ?
decreased by 10%

?We are moving further away from the 2030 Agenda [for sustainable
development],? said Luca De Fraia of ActionAid Italy ?Not only are we missing
the target in terms of quantity, but also the quality of aid is lagging behind
?

Despite a marginal rise in aid going to the least developed countries (from 0
11% in 2017 to 0 12% in 2018), 16 countries, among the poorest in the world,
currently receive only 8% of EU funding, AidWatch found

Guardian Today the headlines, the analysis, the debate - sent direct to you

Read more

?sa Thomasson, from Concord Sweden, called on EU leaders to provide more aid
and ensure it is used effectively to ?make the biggest difference to people
who are most marginalised, excluded or discriminated against and the poorest
and most financially challenged countries?

The report noted progress on what can legitimately be recorded as aid Some
countries had included domestic spending on students, refugees or security in
official figures But such costs ? like debt relief, interest repayments on
loans, or assistance ?tied? to the donor country ? are categorised as
?inflated aid?, since they do not necessarily contribute to development and
are often funds that never leave the EU

This year?s report shows a 25% reduction in inflated aid, while refugee costs
decreased by approximately 35% and the use of aid for debt relief dropped by
66%

Jan van de Poel, policy and advocacy manager at the European Network on Debt
and Development, said he was concerned that the commission is overestimating
the potential for ?blended finance? (linking aid with loans from publicly-
owned institutions or commercial lenders) to help achieve the sustainable

The EU and its member states remain the biggest development donor group in the
world ? investing ?71 9bn (‚Ç¨61bn) in 2018, more than half of global aid ? but
its contribution was 5 8% lower than in 2017, the European NGO network,
Concord, found in its AidWatch report

Progress on meeting the UN target of spending 0 7% of gross national income on
aid, laid down in 1970, has gone into reverse, said the group Their research
showed that aid decreased to 0 47% of the EU?s combined GNI last year,
compared with 0 49% in 2017 and 0 51% in 2016

The UK?s three main political parties have committed to retaining the aid

Aid from five countries ? Italy, Greece, Finland, Austria and Lithuania ?
decreased by 10%

?We are moving further away from the 2030 Agenda [for sustainable
development],? said Luca De Fraia of ActionAid Italy ?Not only are we missing
the target in terms of quantity, but also the quality of aid is lagging behind
?

Less than 10% of EU aid money reaches the countries where it is most needed,
according to a study that found levels of assistance had dropped for the
second year running

The EU and its member states remain the biggest development donor group in the
world ? investing ?71 9bn (‚Ç¨61bn) in 2018, more than half of global aid ? but
its contribution was 5 8% lower than in 2017, the European NGO network,
Concord, found in its AidWatch report

Progress on meeting the UN target of spending 0 7% of gross national income on
aid, laid down in 1970, has gone into reverse, said the group Their research
showed that aid decreased to 0 47% of the EU?s combined GNI last year,
compared with 0 49% in 2017 and 0 51% in 2016

Only Sweden, Luxembourg, Denmark and the UK met the 0 7% commitment

Aid from five countries ? Italy, Greece, Finland, Austria and Lithuania ?

?We are moving further away from the 2030 Agenda [for sustainable

The report noted progress on what can legitimately be recorded as aid Some
countries had included domestic spending on students, refugees or security in
official figures But such costs ? like debt relief, interest repayments on
loans, or assistance ?tied? to the donor country ? are categorised as

Less than 10% of EU aid money reaches the countries where it is most needed,
according to a study that found levels of assistance had dropped for the
second year running

The EU and its member states remain the biggest development donor group in the
world ? investing ?71 9bn (‚Ç¨61bn) in 2018, more than half of global aid ? but
its contribution was 5 8% lower than in 2017, the European NGO network,
Concord, found in its AidWatch report

Progress on meeting the UN target of spending 0 7% of gross national income on
aid, laid down in 1970, has gone into reverse, said the group Their research
showed that aid decreased to 0 47% of the EU?s combined GNI last year,
compared with 0 49% in 2017 and 0 51% in 2016

Only Sweden, Luxembourg, Denmark and the UK met the 0 7% commitment

The UK?s three main political parties have committed to retaining the aid
target

Aid from five countries ? Italy, Greece, Finland, Austria and Lithuania ?
decreased by 10%

?We are moving further away from the 2030 Agenda [for sustainable
development],? said Luca De Fraia of ActionAid Italy ?Not only are we missing
the target in terms of quantity, but also the quality of aid is lagging behind
?

Despite a marginal rise in aid going to the least developed countries (from 0

currently receive only 8% of EU funding, AidWatch found

The report noted progress on what can legitimately be recorded as aid Some
countries had included domestic spending on students, refugees or security in
official figures But such costs ? like debt relief, interest repayments on
loans, or assistance ?tied? to the donor country ? are categorised as
?inflated aid?, since they do not necessarily contribute to development and
are often funds that never leave the EU

This year?s report shows a 25% reduction in inflated aid, while refugee costs
decreased by approximately 35% and the use of aid for debt relief dropped by
66%

Jan van de Poel, policy and advocacy manager at the European Network on Debt
and Development, said he was concerned that the commission is overestimating
the potential for ?blended finance? (linking aid with loans from publicly-
owned institutions or commercial lenders) to help achieve the sustainable
development goals

He pointed out that, as recently as 2016, more than half of all reported
contracts were still awarded to firms in the donor country ?Donors not only
need to untie all aid, but also make sure that their procurement practices are
tailored towards the private sector in developing countries,? he said

Claire Godfrey, interim director of policy, advocacy and research at Bond, the
UK development network, praised the Department for International Development

aid reached the people who need it the most She added that other EU countries
needed to ?step up to the plate?

Fully leverage the development, monitoring and management of Database
with Database Actions
Dear ,
es ist soweit der 11. DBA Stammtisch findet in Wien im grunen Prater
statt. Wir starten um 16h im Vortragsraum der Luftburg Adresse: Prater,
Waldsteingartenstra√üe 128, 1020 Wien. Anschlie√üend gemutlicher
Informationsaustausch bei Speis und Trank.

Unser Thema fur den 11. DBA Stammtisch: Wie kann ich mit der Datenbank
uber den REST WebServices Standard kommunizieren, und wie kann ich Anwendungen
die auf Basis opensource JSON Document Standard entwickelt werden auf der
Datenbank laufen lassen.

Database Actions, fruher bekannt als SQL Developer Web, bringt Ihnen die
Funktionen und die Erfahrung Ihres bevorzugten Datenbank-Desktop-Tools
in Ihren Browser! Database Actions ist eine single-page Webanwendung und wird
von REST Data Services (ORDS) unterstutzt.

Database Actions bietet eine Plattform zum Ausfuhren von Abfragen und
Skripten, die Moglichkeit, Ihr Data Dictionary zu verwalten und zu
durchsuchen, eine REST-Entwicklungsumgebung fur Ihre REST-APIs und AUTOREST-
fahigen Objekte, eine Schnittstelle fur's JSON Document Store (SODA),
eine DBA-Konsole zum Verwalten der Datenbank und vieles mehr.

Im Anschluss an den √úberblick zeigen wir anhand von Live-Demos einige
Anwendungsmoglichkeiten und Funktionen der Database Actions, unter anderem den
Umgang mit dem JSON Document Store.


Vortragender: Josef Weber - Technology Solution Engineer mit Schwerpunkt und
Leidenschaft im Bereich Datascience & Analytics.

Ich freue mich auf den 11.DBA Stammtisch!

22\. - 23. November 2022 in Munchen, Stand Nr. 1
Dieses Jahr findet zum sechsten Mal BIM World Munich statt - die fuhrende
Netzwerkplattform fur alle Beteiligten in der Bau-, Immobilien- und
Stadtentwicklungsbranche. Auch 2022 wird die BIM World Munich wieder einen
umfassenden Marktuberblick uber die neuesten digitalen Methoden,
Dienstleistungen und Technologien bieten - mit einem Ansatz: Ein weiteres und
nachhaltiges Wachstum der AEC-Branche zu ermoglichen!

Auch Oracle Construction and Engineering stellt sich hier dem Fach- und
Entscheider-Publikum der Branche und prasentiert am eigenen Stand
Technologien, Produkt-Trends, Innovationen und ganzheitliche Strategien fur
effizienteres Planen, Bauen und Betreiben.

Erfahren Sie bei uns, wie man

  * strategisch plant, effektiv baut und intelligent arbeitet mit Oracle Aconex und Oracle Primavera Cloud.
  * fortschrittliche Prozesse von der Projektauswahl uber den Bau bis hin zum Facility Management nutzt.
  * eine intelligente Plattform fur ganzheitliche Construction und Engineering-Prozesse im unternehmensweiten IT-√ñkosystem einsetzt.
  * mit smarten Integrationen fur durchgehende Bearbeitung, optimale Transparenz und luckenloses Asset-Lifecycle-Management sorgt



und vieles mehr.

Kommen Sie an unserem Stand Nr. 1 vorbei und diskutieren Sie mit unseren
Spezialisten und Technologie-Experten.

Wir freuen uns auf Ihren Besuch!

Ihr Oracle Construction and Engineering Team

Hello,

Welcome to your Overleaf Premium Features Trial! We really appreciate your
support of Overleaf and are excited for you to use our premium features and
get the most out of your trial.

**During your trial period, be sure to check out these premium features:**

1\. **Increased compile timeout** : You now have more time for compilation (to
generate a PDF of your document) before receiving a timeout error message.

  * Compile Timeout: Read More

2\. **Full document history and versioning** : View the entire history of your
project with the ability to revert to previous versions of your document from
your project history (versus only 24 hours of history availability on a free
Overleaf account). No more fear of losing work or making changes you can‚Äôt
undo.

  * History: Read More
  * Versioning: Read More

3\. **Advanced reference search** : You can search by citation key, and our
premium feature allows the added ability to search by author, title, year, or
journal.

  * Advanced Reference Search: Read More

4\. **Reference manager sync** : You can link your Mendeley and Zotero
accounts to your Overleaf account, allowing you to import your reference
library and keep your Overleaf document in sync with the references stored in
Mendeley / Zotero.

  * Reference Manager Sync: Read More

5\. **Dropbox Sync** : You can link your Dropbox account to your Overleaf
account, allowing 2-way integration with Dropbox

  * Dropbox Sync: Read More

6\. **Git and GitHub integration** : You can configure your Overleaf project
to sync directly with a repository on GitHub, or you can use raw git access.
This allows you to work offline and sync your files whenever you come back
online. You can also use our Overleaf Git Bridge integration, which lets you
git clone, push and pull changes between the online Overleaf editor, and your
local offline git repository.

  * Git, GitHub and Git Bridge: Read More

7\. **Symbol Palette** : A quick and convenient tool to insert math symbols
into your document.

  * Symbol Palette: Read More

8\. **Online tutorials and knowledge base** : We have an extensive online
knowledge base providing a wide range of platform guidance, LaTeX tutorials,
technical articles, and webinars.

  * LaTeX tutorials: Read More
  * Knowledge base: Read More
  * Technical articles: Read More
  * Webinars: Read More

cancel at any time via your subscription page on your dashboard. If you‚Äôd like
to continue your subscription after your trial, you‚Äôre all set!

Please let us know if we can provide any additional support or answer any
questions - and we‚Äôd love to hear your feedback!

Thanks again for supporting Overleaf - Happy TeXing!

The Overleaf Team

Dear Mr.,

For the 4th time, a large-scale student survey at Saxon universities is being
conducted this year with the support of the S√§chsisches Staatsministerium f√ºr
Wissenschaft und Kunst (SMWK). We would like to invite you to participate in
this survey. At the same time, we refer to the attached letter of invitation
from the Minister of Science, Mr. Sebastian Gemkow.

The existing university statistics with their information on the number of
students, final examinations, duration of studies, etc. are by far not
sufficient for the universities to gain a comprehensive picture of the study
situation and study quality. This is only possible if you, as a student, are
able to give an unvarnished account of your positive as well as negative study
experiences and report on your course of study, your further study planning
and your personal study situation from your own point of view. This survey
offers you this opportunity.

The questionnaire is available in German and English. You will find your
personal access to the questionnaire here:
https://befragung.zqa.tu-dresden.de/qp/l/nQ4XcOGZ8gMw

The personal access link to the questionnaire prevents completion by strangers
or repeated completion. This link will not be stored with your information in
the questionnaire. Answering the questionnaire will take about 20 minutes.
Please answer the questionnaire within two weeks if possible. Within the
survey period, you can interrupt answering the questionnaire at any point and
continue at a later time with your personal access link.

You have been randomly selected by your university for the survey from among
the students. The quality of the study depends very much on a high level of
participation. Also on behalf of the SMWK and your university, we ask you to
participate in this study.

If you are interested in the results of the previous Saxon Student Surveys,
you can find the research reports on the project website of the Saxon Student
Survey. The results of the current survey are also expected to be published
there in December 2022.

All information you provide in the questionnaire is voluntary and will be
treated in strict compliance with data protection regulations. The anonymity
of your data is of course guaranteed. The implementation has been coordinated
with the data protection officer of the TU Dresden. Detailed information on
data protection can be found on the start page of the survey.
If you have any questions, please do not hesitate to send us an e-mail.

Yours sincerely and thank you for your support

Prof. Dr. Karl Lenz

Dear student,

Due to the contract between Studentenwerk Leipzig and Mitteldeutscher
Verkehrsverbund MDV, the semester ticket is available to all students in
Leipzig. This contract ends with end of the summer semester of 2024, and
negotiations for an extension of the contract must begin in April of this
year.

It is necessary to learn more about the **demand** for the semester ticket so
that the semester ticket committee, together with Studentenwerk Leipzig, can
best represent the **interests of the students with regard to public transport
mobility** in these contract negotiations.

We would therefore be pleased if you would take part in the approximately
**5-minute survey**. Even if you hardly ever or never use public transport,
your answers are interesting for us and provide us with important insights.

The survey is available at the following link until **17.03.2023** :

 **http://mobilitaet-en.daten-erhebung.de** ****

Of course, your information will be treated strictly confidentially, and the
data will be evaluated anonymously. It is not possible to draw any conclusions
about your person under any circumstances. Nevertheless, for reasons of data
protection, we require your explicit consent that you have read the data
protection declaration and agree to the data processing. To do this, click on
the button **" I accept the data protection declaration and take part in the
survey."** if you agree to the evaluation of your data. In order to ensure the
anonymity of the participants, we would like to ask you to fill in the free
text fields without personal information, if possible.

If you have any questions concerning the survey, please feel free to contact
us (kommunikation@studentenwerk-leipzig.de) or the survey team of the Conomic
agency (info@conomic.de) via e-mail.



Thank you very much for your support.

Your Semester Ticket Committee of the Studentenwerk Leipzig
